![d_cur](data:image/png;base64,)

## The curve fitted after choosing a very small value of the learning rate since the value of error was raised to power 3 leading to a very large value. I tried gradient clipping too but it was not much useful. 

## (d.) The case was somewhat similar for the other part of polynomial regression too. The error was overflowing and hence I could not get a good approximation of the curve. The results are little poor in this case. The curve can be seen in the respective notebook. 

## Just to summarise, what I felt was that the cost function which were convex or which had lower exponents associated with them were easier to deal with since it was much more convenient to apply gradient descent on them.
